{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a7fcaa3d-9976-45f2-a18c-d776015c4e63","content":"Use MAUI's conditional compilation with `#if` directives in `MauiProgram.cs`:\n\n```csharp\npublic static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()\n{\n    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();\n    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();\n\n#if ANDROID\n    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Android.AndroidNotificationService>();\n#elif IOS\n    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.iOS.iOSNotificationService>();\n#elif WINDOWS\n    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Windows.WindowsNotificationService>();\n#endif\n\n    return builder.Build();\n}\n```\n\nEach platform implementation lives under its respective `Platforms/` folder (which already has the correct build target set in the default MAUI project).\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- The `ANDROID`, `IOS`, and `WINDOWS` symbols are defined automatically by the MAUI SDK per target framework — no manual setup needed.\n- Only the relevant platform code compiles into each binary, so there's no runtime risk of missing types.\n- Inject `INotificationService` via constructor injection anywhere in shared code as usual.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f1525d2b-948a-4ec8-8791-d43cf152e1d2","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI dependency injection — specifically how to register platform-specific implementations of an `INotificationService` in `MauiProgram.cs`. This is a general knowledge question, not a codebase task.","outputTokens":365,"requestId":"143B:2950B:6A0DA0D:7271EC7:6A03CE43"},"id":"5ca93780-d30f-4cd6-bb63-a4e23f4522ec","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:05:16.043Z","parentId":"eb277c8e-f315-480c-8540-fcdf5f5032d8"}
